<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,437,1540,1567]" box="[189,437,1540,1567]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,437,1540,1567]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,437,1540,1567]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Conservation status</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1586,1717]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Known from only one locality. Given its apparent rarity and following the recommendation of 
<bibRefCitation author="Callmander M. W. &amp; Schatz G. E. &amp; Lowry P. P." box="[189,486,1620,1647]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1047 - 1050" refId="ref18813" refString="Callmander M. W., Schatz G. E. &amp; Lowry P. P. 2005. IUCN Red List assessment and the global strategy for plant conservation: taxonomists must act now. Taxon 54: 1047 - 1050." type="journal article" year="2005">
Callmander 
<emphasis box="[337,398,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al.</emphasis>
(2005)
</bibRefCitation>
to avoid the Data Deficient category, we consider the species as vulnerable (VU D2) based on its restricted area of occupancy (D2) and the high human pressure present in the entire area resulting in a general decline of suitable habitats (dry forest) for the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
